1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,785
What about missing data?

2
00:00:01,785 --> 00:00:04,125
If we have missing data in a particular column,

3
00:00:04,125 --> 00:00:05,795
there's a number of things we can do.

4
00:00:05,795 --> 00:00:08,320
But first, let's talk about formats.

5
00:00:08,320 --> 00:00:13,560
What if missing data doesn't come in the typical NAN format that we're used to?

6
00:00:13,560 --> 00:00:15,120
What if the missing data, for example,

7
00:00:15,120 --> 00:00:18,735
is written down as a hyphen or an asterisk when we were gathering the data?

8
00:00:18,735 --> 00:00:22,320
Let's start by importing our pandas and numpy libraries and reading

9
00:00:22,320 --> 00:00:25,950
in a small synthetic dataset that contains two columns,

10
00:00:25,950 --> 00:00:27,675
Assessment score 1 and 2.

11
00:00:27,675 --> 00:00:29,760
They don't really mean anything and are just columns

12
00:00:29,760 --> 00:00:32,400
containing random values for the purpose of this walkthrough.

13
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:34,755
The data has 10,000 rows,

14
00:00:34,755 --> 00:00:37,515
as we can see with the describe method.

15
00:00:37,515 --> 00:00:40,490
Notice how the Assessment score 2 column doesn't

16
00:00:40,490 --> 00:00:43,220
even pop up in the described methods numerical summary,

17
00:00:43,220 --> 00:00:47,830
even though the values of this column seem to be all integers.

18
00:00:47,830 --> 00:00:52,505
In additional, checking the info method summary on the dataset,

19
00:00:52,505 --> 00:00:55,235
we see that it suggests that the Assessment score 1 has

20
00:00:55,235 --> 00:00:59,840
four missing values and there isn't any missing values in the Assessment score 2 column.

21
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:02,030
This is because missing values in

22
00:01:02,030 --> 00:01:05,405
the Assessment score 2 column are represented by hashtag signs.

23
00:01:05,405 --> 00:01:08,465
For example when I randomly pull up some sample data here,

24
00:01:08,465 --> 00:01:13,315
we can see that the last row is using a hashtag sign for this column.

25
00:01:13,315 --> 00:01:18,215
But how many data points are actually having this hashtag sign and where are they?

26
00:01:18,215 --> 00:01:20,480
You can use two methods to identify this.

27
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:21,665
The is in method,

28
00:01:21,665 --> 00:01:23,740
and then you can use the replace method.

29
00:01:23,740 --> 00:01:26,540
The is in method helps you identify whether

30
00:01:26,540 --> 00:01:30,365
a certain character is in your dataset and returns all the rows that apply.

31
00:01:30,365 --> 00:01:32,820
For example we first select

32
00:01:32,820 --> 00:01:37,035
the Assessment score 2 column from the DataFrame df Assessment score 2.

33
00:01:37,035 --> 00:01:41,210
Then we use the is in method with hashtag as input to check

34
00:01:41,210 --> 00:01:45,475
if the values in this Assessment score 2 column is the character hashtag.

35
00:01:45,475 --> 00:01:47,840
This will then return a Boolean series

36
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:50,495
true if the value is a hashtag and false otherwise.

37
00:01:50,495 --> 00:01:56,045
Df.loc is used to filter the DataFrame based on the Boolean series generated by is in.

38
00:01:56,045 --> 00:01:59,610
It then only selects the rows where the condition is true, i.e.

39
00:01:59,610 --> 00:02:03,140
rows where this Assessment score 2 column contains the hashtag character,

40
00:02:03,140 --> 00:02:07,405
as we can see here, and neatly displays it to us in a DataFrame format.

41
00:02:07,405 --> 00:02:10,490
Now next, the replace method is helping

42
00:02:10,490 --> 00:02:13,190
us with replacing a specific value in the dataframe.

43
00:02:13,190 --> 00:02:15,425
For this particular second column,

44
00:02:15,425 --> 00:02:20,150
we're going to go ahead and use the indexing again and use the dot replace method for

45
00:02:20,150 --> 00:02:25,640
replace the hashtag with a nan value or not a number value in the numpy format.

46
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:28,730
This np.nan comes from the numpy library

47
00:02:28,730 --> 00:02:32,270
and it's used to represent missing or null values in a DataFrame.

48
00:02:32,270 --> 00:02:36,155
Then this modified column with the replace the values is assigned back

49
00:02:36,155 --> 00:02:40,300
to the original Assignment score 2 column in the DataFrame.

50
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:43,325
Running the is in method, again,

51
00:02:43,325 --> 00:02:45,830
we can see there's no more instances of hashtags now

52
00:02:45,830 --> 00:02:48,745
that we've converted these hashtags to np.nans.

53
00:02:48,745 --> 00:02:51,500
When we use the sum function to count the number of

54
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:55,070
missing values on the.isna method we can

55
00:02:55,070 --> 00:02:57,620
identify assessment score has four missing values and

56
00:02:57,620 --> 00:03:02,280
Assessment score 2 has 92 missing values.

